    consequences: 'Sin in Sikhism deepens one\'s entrapment in Maya (illusion) and perpetuates the cycle of birth and death (reincarnation). The five vices corrupt the mind and prevent the soul from experiencing union with God. Sikh scripture describes sinners as suffering spiritual blindness, inner turmoil, and distance from Waheguru. Unlike some traditions, Sikhism does not emphasize hell as eternal punishment but rather as states of consciousness created by one\'s own actions and mental state.',
    forgiveness: 'Sikhism teaches that God (Waheguru) is infinitely compassionate and forgiving. Forgiveness comes through: (1) Ardas — sincere prayer asking God for forgiveness, (2) Naam Simran — meditating on God\'s name to purify the mind, (3) Seva — selfless service to others, and (4) Sangat — association with holy congregation. The Guru Granth Sahib repeatedly emphasizes that sincere devotion and surrender to God\'s will (Hukam) can erase all sins. There is no priestly class needed for forgiveness — the relationship is direct between the individual and Waheguru.',
