    greetings: '"Namaste" or "Namaskar" with palms together is universally appropriate. In South India, touching elders\' feet is a sign of deep respect. "Jai Shri Ram," "Jai Shri Krishna," or "Hari Om" are devotional greetings used by practitioners.',
    dressCode: 'Modest clothing is expected at temples. Traditional Indian clothing is always appreciated but not required. White is worn at funerals; bright colors (especially red) at weddings and celebrations. Avoid black at auspicious occasions. Remove leather items in strict temples. Women may be asked to cover their heads in some temple traditions.',
    dietaryRules: 'Extremely diverse. Many Hindus are lacto-vegetarian (no meat, fish, or eggs, but dairy is fine). Beef is universally avoided. Some families avoid onion and garlic on religious days. During festivals and fasting periods, specific dietary restrictions apply. When hosting Hindus, vegetarian food is the safe default. Alcohol is frowned upon by devout practitioners.',
    sacredSpaces: 'Temples (Mandir) range from grand complexes to small family shrines. Remove shoes, silence phones, dress modestly. Ring the bell upon entering (it invites the deity\'s attention and clears the mind). Sit on the floor if there are no chairs. Some temples restrict non-Hindu entry — respect this. Home shrines (puja rooms) are treated as sacred — ask before entering.',
