    greetings: 'The "anjali" (palms pressed together at chest level with a slight bow) is appropriate across Buddhist cultures. In Thailand: "Sawasdee." In Tibet: "Tashi Delek." In Japanese Buddhist settings: a simple bow. Address monks with appropriate titles: "Bhante" (Theravada), "Venerable," or "Rinpoche" (Tibetan).',
    dressCode: 'Modest, subdued clothing. Cover shoulders and knees at temples. In Thailand, long pants/skirts and covered shoulders are required. White clothing is appropriate for meditation retreats and temple visits. Avoid revealing clothing. Remove hats in temple buildings. Some temples provide shawls or sarongs for visitors.',
    dietaryRules: 'Varies by tradition. Many Mahayana Buddhists are vegetarian (especially in Chinese, Korean, and Vietnamese traditions). Theravada monks eat whatever is offered to them, including meat. In general, Buddhists value non-harming, so vegetarian options are always appropriate. Alcohol is discouraged but observance varies.',
